So what is the optimal S?¶

Simply put, if we know that the array we are getting is going to be more or less sorted, we use a bigger value for S.

If we know the array is not very sorted (descending in the worst case), we use a smaller S.

This makes sense, as:

  1. Insertion Sort "short circuits" comparisons for sorted portions of the array, leading to less time taken.
  2. Merge Sort is faster for unsorted portions than Insertion Sort.

Why not use math to find S?¶

You can, but it will not be accurate (which our experimental data clearly shows), because it does not take into account real-world issues, such as:

  1. Recursion overhead.
  2. Element comparisons.
  3. Copying memory data. etc...

b) Merge vs Hybrid Sort¶

Checking Ascending array¶

In [7]:
sb.lineplot(data=results[results.input_type == "ascending"],
            x="size", y="comparisons", hue="sort_type")
Out[7]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='size', ylabel='comparisons'>

In the best case, we can see Insertion Sort making O(n) comparisons.

Merge Sort continues its divide-and-conquer approach (and so does Hybrid Sort), which results in more comparisons, but Hybrid Sort makes less comparisons to Merge Sort as it implements insertion under a certain threshold (which in this case we have decided on as 30).

For the sharp increase in key comparison after the size reaches a multiple of the previous threshold value,

(2i)*S , for i = natural numbers,

It is because the merge sort algorithm has to be called 2i-1 more time (2i = size n/threshold S) over the next 2i increase in size, to split the array into a size that is less than the threshold value, therefore increasing the number of key comparisons significantly for merge sort in a short span and hence the hybrid sort.

Checking Descending array¶

Based on the result in part (a), we know that the threshold we should set for descending ordered arrays should be around 35-55.

In this case, we use 35 as the threshold.

In [15]:
sb.lineplot(data=results[results.input_type == "descending"][:250], 
            x="size", y="comparisons", hue="sort_type")
Out[15]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='size', ylabel='comparisons'>

We can see that the Hybrid Sort follows the same number of comparisons as Insertion Sort until the threshold.

For the sharp decrease in key comparison after the size reaches a multiple of the previous threshold value (2i)*S , for i = natural numbers, it is similar to the reason for the ascending array.

The merge sort algorithm has to be called 2i-1 more time (2i = size n/threshold S) over the next 2i increase in size, to split the array into a size that is less than the threshold value, which will be essentially half the size of the threshold.

This decreases the number of elements for the insertion sort, which will reduce the number of key comparisons significantly as a descending array is the worst case for insertion sort. This in turn decreases the key comparisons for the hybrid sort.

Checking Random array¶

Based on the result in part (a), we know that the threshold we should set for random ordered arrays should be around 150-170.

In this case, we use 165 as the threshold.

In [9]:
sb.lineplot(data=results[results.input_type == "random"], 
            x="size", y="comparisons", hue="sort_type")
Out[9]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='size', ylabel='comparisons'>

Likewise, we see Hybrid Sort following the same number of comparisons as Insertion Sort until the threshold.

Notes regarding number of comparisons¶

In all cases (except ascending order), we can see that Insertion Sort makes more comparisons than either Merge Sort or Hybrid Sort.

In addition, the number of comparisons made by Hybrid Sort is always more than Merge Sort. This makes sense, since Hybrid Sort makes use of Insertion Sort at smaller array lengths.

Using results of study (comparing Merge vs Hybrid Sort runtimes)¶

Now that we know the thresholds required, let us take a look at the timings for Hybrid Sort for random ordered arrays, using a good guess for the threshold.

For random ordered arrays, we can see that Hybrid Sort is able to achieve lower runtimes than a pure Merge Sort by setting a good guess for a threshold (in this case, it is 165 for random).
